 0302:         """
 0303:         Puts the status register into an 8-bit value.  Bit 6 is set high always, bit 5 (the "B flag") is set according
 0304:         to the b_flag argument.  This should be high if called from an instruction (PHP or BRK) instruction, low if
 0305:         the call came from a hardware interrupt (IRQ or NMI).
 0306:         """

 0312:                 + self.I * SR_I_MASK
 0313:                 + self.Z * SR_Z_MASK
+0314:                 + self.C * SR_C_MASK) & 0xFF   # this final and forces it to be treated as unsigned
  __pyx_r = (((((((((__pyx_v_self->N * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_N_MASK) + (__pyx_v_self->V * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_V_MASK)) + __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_X_MASK) + (__pyx_v_b_flag * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_B_MASK)) + (__pyx_v_self->D * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_D_MASK)) + (__pyx_v_self->I * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_I_MASK)) + (__pyx_v_self->Z * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_Z_MASK)) + (__pyx_v_self->C * __pyx_e_3nes_6cycore_7mos6502_SR_C_MASK)) & 0xFF);

 0513:         # Set the interrupt disable flag.  But there seems to be disagreement in the sources as to whether or not the
 0514:         # I flag is set if this is a BRK instruction.
 0515:         # The following sources have it set:
 0516:         #   https://www.masswerk.at/6502/6502_instruction_set.html#BRK
 0517:         #   blargg's instruction tests (15-brk)

 0519:         #   http://www.obelisk.me.uk/6502/reference.html#BRK
 0520:         #   http://www.6502.org/tutorials/6502opcodes.html#BRK
 0521:         #   https://www.csh.rit.edu/~moffitt/docs/6502.html#BRK
 0522:         # Since blargg's tests run on a hardware NES, we follow that behaviour

 0526:         """

 0904:         """
 0905:         Subtract memory plus carry flag from A and put the result in A (i.e. A := A - M - ~C).
 0906:         The carry flag is set if A - M - ~C >= 0, i.e. if no borrow is necessary (allows chaining of
 0907:         subtract instructions).
 0908:         The overflow (V) flag is set if there is a (signed) overflow.
 0909:         Overflow occurs when the result is either too negative or too positive to be held in the available 8 bits.
 0910:         This can happen in two cases:
 0911:           1) when A is +ve and v is -ve; this should create a +ve number, so if result is -ve that is overflow
 0912:           2) when A is -ve and v is +ve; this should create a -ve number, so if result is +ve that is overflow
 0913:         """
